<h1>Ideation</h1>
<h3>Ideation Eloquence</h3>
<p>Generally, the word “eloquence” is defined in terms of language. To be eloquent is to have the ability to use language, both written and spoken, with fluency, and to be able to deploy this ability to transfer knowledge, create understanding, and /
  or persuade others.
</p>
<p>In design, however, teams often find themselves in need of describing insights that are nuanced, systems that are complex, and products or services that do not yet exist. In these situations, words sometimes “fail us”; one can’t quite figure how
  how to say what needs to be said. The sequential and rules-based nature of verbal and written language creates immediate heirarchies, while the avialability of words and phrases to describe familiar ideas means that unfamiliar or perhaps partially
  formed ideas get second place simply because designers do not have the words to express them.</p>
<p>For these reasons, designers often draw on forms of communication alternative to spoken and written forms. These channels include creating and / or collecting drawings, images, sounds, and gestures in order to acheive four primary goals:
  <br>
  <ul class="usa-list">
    <li>To
      <strong>explore</strong>
      nuances in a proposal, system, or idea</li>
    <li>To
      <strong>understand</strong>
      those nuances</li>
    <li>To
      <strong>clarify</strong>
      those nuances, especially if they act within a complex system</li>
    <li>To
      <strong>communicate</strong>
      the steps above to others who may or may not be present</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Important to note: this is not a rigid sequence of steps, but is instead a collection of goals that using linguistic alternates can allow teams and designers to acheive. At times, teams simply need to make a drawing or put together images or
    sounds so that they, either as individuals or as a team, can understand what they are working on.
  </p>

  <h2>Elements of Ideation</h2>
