  <h2>Visualizing Ideation</h2>
  <p>
    <img src="/images/ideation-idea1.svg" class="height-card" alt="Visualizing Ideation Idea 1">
  </p>
  <p>Sometimes teams find themselves with a particularly complex system or idea to show.
  </p>
  <p>
    <img src="/images/ideation-idea2.svg" class="height-card" alt="Visualizing Ideation Idea 2">
  </p>
  <p>Here are the four separate tangram puzzles from the Elements of Ideation section stacked on top of each other in different orders. These stacks show how, in attempting to express ideas, teams often simply combine different research elements,
    approaches, solutions, and values in a big, unwieldy stack in order to build a model of an idea. The benefit to working this way is that (a) the team is working on paper; these models have no real function except as a means by which to work through
    ideas and (b) these models can show the different facets, complexities, and points of interference that existing processes and solutions might have.
  </p>
  <p>
    <img src="/images/ideation-idea3.svg" class="height-card" alt="Visualizing Ideation Idea 3">
  </p>
  <p>Although the rules of using tangram puzzles have been violated in this example, the combination of puzzles allows for more complex shapes. As we will see in the next section, designers often combine different elements from their research and
    existing products and services in new or expected ways to explore, understand, clarify, and communicate their ideas.
  </p>
  <p>
    <img src="/images/ideation-idea4.svg" class="height-card" alt="Visualizing Ideation Idea 4">
  </p>
  <p>The complexity of these shapes is not a desired final state of a design phase. These composite shapes are a way to show all that is happening in an idea, not forms for design solutions themselves. As was said in the Principles section, getting to
    simple is hard.</p>

  <h3>Case Study</h3>
  <h4>USAJOBS Mission Critical Hiring Paths Diagram</h4>
  <p>
    <a href="/images/ideation-usajobs_mco.pdf">
      <img src="/images/ideation-usajobs_mco.png" alt="USAJOBS Mission Critical Hiring Paths Diagram">Click to enlarge</a>
  </p>

  <p>This diagram shows the hiring path of various mission critical positions in the federal government. As part of the USA Jobs redesign, this digram displays the idea of hiring for these important positions.
  </p>
  <p>A simple glance can show a reader that this is an incredibly complex problem involving multiple groups and a systems. Through building this illustrative stack of the components of the hiring path: people, systems, and stages, the USA Jobs team at
    The Lab was able to not come up with a solution for hiring, but instead show the system and its possible throughlines in a global manner.
  </p>
  <h3>Diagrams</h3>
  <p>Diagrams like this one are a common application of drawing and visual communication in government. They can be used to give form to items that, in reality, don’t have a physical, tangible form, such as this Hiring Paths process or the
    organizational chart of an office.
  </p>

